<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--                   1. PURPOSE OF THE WORK                           -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>1. Purpose of the Work</h3>

<p>In India, millions of small and micro businesses&mdash;including local grocery stores, bakeries, clothing shops, salons, pharmacies, and restaurants&mdash;operate with little to no digital presence. According to a report by the Internet and Mobile Association of India (IAMAI), over 63 million MSMEs in India lack any form of online storefront. While large e-commerce platforms such as Amazon and Flipkart dominate the online retail space, they are often inaccessible or economically unviable for small shopkeepers who wish to serve their immediate local community.</p>

<p>The primary barriers preventing these shopkeepers from establishing a digital presence include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Lack of Technical Expertise:</b> Most small business owners possess limited knowledge of web development, hosting, or domain management.</li>
  <li><b>High Cost of Development:</b> Hiring a developer or subscribing to premium website builders (such as Shopify or Wix) involves recurring costs that are impractical for micro businesses.</li>
  <li><b>Complexity of Existing Tools:</b> Even no-code builders require a learning curve and produce websites that may not suit Indian business contexts (e.g., WhatsApp-based ordering, Indian Rupee pricing, vernacular aesthetics).</li>
  <li><b>No Need for Full E-Commerce:</b> Many shopkeepers do not need shopping carts, payment gateways, or inventory management systems. They need a simple, attractive product catalogue that allows customers to browse and place orders via familiar channels like WhatsApp.</li>
</ul>

<p>The purpose of this dissertation is to design and develop an <b>AI-powered static website generator</b> that enables small shopkeepers to create professional, mobile-responsive marketing pages for their businesses in minutes, with zero coding knowledge. The generated website serves as a <b>static product catalogue</b> with integrated <b>WhatsApp-based ordering</b>&mdash;customers can view products, see prices, and tap a button to place an order directly via WhatsApp with a pre-filled message containing the product details.</p>

<p>The system uses <b>Google Gemini AI</b> (large language model) to intelligently generate a complete, self-contained HTML page tailored to the business type, including appropriate colour schemes, typography, layout, and responsive design&mdash;all embedded in a single downloadable HTML file that can be hosted for free on platforms like GitHub Pages, Netlify, or even shared as a file.</p>

<p>This work aims to bridge the digital divide for India&rsquo;s small businesses by providing a tool that is simple, free, and immediately useful&mdash;aligned with the Government of India&rsquo;s Digital India initiative and the growing trend of conversational commerce via WhatsApp in the Indian market.</p>

<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--                    2. EXPECTED OUTCOME                             -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>2. Expected Outcome</h3>

<p>The expected outcome of this dissertation is a fully functional, production-ready web application that delivers the following results:</p>

<h4>2.1 Primary Deliverables</h4>
<ol>
  <li><b>AI-Powered Website Generator Application:</b> A React-based web application where shopkeepers can input their business details and product information through a simple, guided two-step form, and receive a fully generated static website within 15&ndash;30 seconds.</li>

  <li><b>Static Marketing Pages:</b> Single-file HTML websites that include:
    <ul>
      <li>Professional, business-type-specific design (colour scheme, layout, fonts)</li>
      <li>Hero banner with business branding</li>
      <li>Responsive product catalogue grid with images, prices, and unit types</li>
      <li>WhatsApp &ldquo;Order Now&rdquo; buttons on each product card with pre-filled order messages</li>
      <li>Contact section with business details (phone, email, address)</li>
      <li>Mobile-first responsive design that works across devices</li>
      <li>CSS animations and modern UI/UX elements</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li><b>WhatsApp Integration for Ordering:</b> Each product card contains a WhatsApp button that opens the WhatsApp application (or WhatsApp Web) with a pre-composed message containing the product name, price, and a polite order request directed to the shopkeeper&rsquo;s phone number.</li>
</ol>

<h4>2.2 Technical Outcomes</h4>
<ul>
  <li>A robust multi-model fallback system leveraging multiple Google Gemini AI models for reliable website generation.</li>
  <li>A single-file output architecture requiring no server, database, or backend infrastructure for serving the generated website.</li>
  <li>Preview functionality with desktop and mobile views to help shopkeepers verify their website before downloading.</li>
  <li>Download capability that allows the generated HTML to be saved and deployed anywhere.</li>
</ul>

<h4>2.3 Business Outcomes</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Reduced time-to-market for small businesses to establish an online presence&mdash;from weeks/months to minutes.</li>
  <li>Zero technical barrier for shopkeepers.</li>
  <li>Zero recurring cost as the generated output is a standalone static file.</li>
  <li>Leveraging WhatsApp&mdash;India&rsquo;s most widely used messaging platform with over 500 million users&mdash;as the order channel, eliminating the need for payment gateway integration or complex checkout flows.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--                   3. LITERATURE REVIEW                             -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>3. Literature Review</h3>

<h4>3.1 Small Business Digitalisation in India</h4>
<p>The digital transformation of micro, small, and medium enterprises (MSMEs) has been a focal area for both academic research and industry initiatives. According to the Ministry of MSME, India has approximately 63.4 million MSMEs that contribute around 30% of India&rsquo;s GDP. However, a 2023 report by NASSCOM highlights that less than 10% of these businesses have a meaningful online presence. The COVID-19 pandemic accelerated the urgency for digital adoption, with local businesses forced to explore online channels for survival (Sharma &amp; Gupta, 2021).</p>

<h4>3.2 No-Code and Low-Code Website Builders</h4>
<p>The no-code movement has gained significant traction with platforms like Wix, Squarespace, Shopify, and WordPress. Sahni et al. (2022) conducted a comparative study of no-code platforms and found that while they reduce development complexity, they still require familiarisation with drag-and-drop interfaces, template customisation, and ongoing subscription costs. For India&rsquo;s price-sensitive micro-business segment, even $10&ndash;$30/month subscription costs are prohibitive (Patel &amp; Mehta, 2022).</p>

<h4>3.3 AI-Driven Web Development</h4>
<p>Recent advancements in large language models (LLMs) have enabled AI-assisted and AI-generated web development. Tools like GitHub Copilot, Vercel&rsquo;s v0, and various GPT-based code generators have demonstrated the ability to produce functional HTML/CSS/JavaScript code from natural language prompts (Chen et al., 2021). Google&rsquo;s Gemini model family, which this dissertation uses, represents state-of-the-art multi-modal AI capable of generating structured, contextually appropriate code (Google DeepMind, 2024).</p>

<p>Prior work by Ravi &amp; Krishnan (2023) demonstrated the feasibility of using LLMs to generate business-specific web templates, achieving over 85% user satisfaction in usability tests. However, their approach required manual post-generation editing, which this dissertation aims to minimise through carefully crafted prompts and business-context-aware generation.</p>

<h4>3.4 Conversational Commerce and WhatsApp Business</h4>
<p>Conversational commerce&mdash;the intersection of messaging apps and shopping&mdash;has emerged as a dominant trend in developing markets. A 2023 study by Statista reported that India has over 535 million WhatsApp users, making it the largest market globally. WhatsApp Business API and click-to-chat features have enabled businesses to receive orders, provide support, and process payments directly through conversations (Meta, 2023).</p>

<p>Research by Das &amp; Roy (2022) found that 72% of surveyed Indian consumers preferred placing orders via WhatsApp over traditional e-commerce checkout flows for local purchases. This finding validates the approach of using WhatsApp as the ordering mechanism in the generated websites.</p>

<h4>3.5 Static Site Generation</h4>
<p>The JAMstack (JavaScript, APIs, Markup) architecture and static site generation have become mainstream for performance, security, and cost efficiency. Platforms like Netlify and Vercel offer free hosting for static sites. Research by Biilmann &amp; Hawksworth (2019) demonstrated that static sites offer superior load times, reduced security vulnerabilities (no server-side processing), and zero hosting costs&mdash;making them ideal for small business use cases where simplicity and reliability are paramount.</p>

<h4>3.6 Gap Analysis</h4>
<p>While individual solutions exist for no-code website building, AI code generation, and WhatsApp commerce, <b>no existing tool combines all three</b> into a single, frictionless experience tailored specifically for Indian small businesses. This dissertation addresses this gap by building an AI-powered generator that produces static marketing pages with integrated WhatsApp ordering, requiring zero technical knowledge and zero ongoing costs.</p>

<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--            4. EXISTING PROCESS AND ITS LIMITATIONS                 -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>4. Existing Process and Its Limitations</h3>

<p>Currently, small shopkeepers who wish to establish an online presence must rely on one of the following approaches:</p>

<h4>4.1 Hiring a Web Developer</h4>
<p>Many shopkeepers hire freelance developers to build custom websites. This process typically involves multiple meetings, requirement gathering, iterative design approvals, and a development cycle spanning 2&ndash;6 weeks. The cost ranges from &#8377;5,000 to &#8377;50,000 depending on complexity. Furthermore, ongoing maintenance, updates, and hosting add recurring expenses.</p>
<p><b>Limitations:</b> Expensive, time-consuming, dependency on a third party, and difficult to update product listings independently.</p>

<h4>4.2 Using No-Code Platforms (Wix, Shopify, WordPress)</h4>
<p>Platforms like Wix and Shopify provide drag-and-drop interfaces. However, they require account creation, template selection, manual customisation, and ongoing subscriptions. Shopify plans start at $39/month (approximately &#8377;3,200/month), which is significant for a small shop generating &#8377;10,000&ndash;&#8377;50,000 monthly revenue.</p>
<p><b>Limitations:</b> Recurring costs, learning curve, English-centric UI, templates not tailored for Indian local businesses, and over-engineered features (payment gateways, inventory management) that small shopkeepers do not need.</p>

<h4>4.3 Social Media Presence Only</h4>
<p>Many shopkeepers rely solely on Facebook pages, Instagram shops, or WhatsApp Status for product promotion. While this is free, it lacks a professional, permanent catalogue. Posts get buried in feeds, there is no structured product display, and discoverability is algorithmically limited.</p>
<p><b>Limitations:</b> No permanent product catalogue, dependency on platform algorithms, unprofessional presentation, and limited to followers/contacts only.</p>

<h4>4.4 Google Business Profile / JustDial Listings</h4>
<p>Some shopkeepers create listings on Google Business or JustDial. While useful for discoverability, these platforms do not allow product-level showcase, custom branding, or direct ordering mechanisms.</p>
<p><b>Limitations:</b> No product catalogue, no ordering capability, limited customisation, and competing listings appear alongside.</p>

<h4>4.5 Summary of Limitations</h4>

