<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--       5. JUSTIFICATION FOR SELECTING A PARTICULAR METHODOLOGY      -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>5. Justification for Selecting a Particular Methodology</h3>

<p>The methodology for this dissertation was selected based on the following rationale:</p>

<h4>5.1 React.js as the Frontend Framework</h4>
<p>React.js was chosen for building the website generator application due to its component-based architecture, which naturally maps to the multi-step form workflow (BusinessForm &rarr; ProductForm &rarr; WebsitePreview). React&rsquo;s virtual DOM ensures smooth UI transitions and real-time preview updates. Its vast ecosystem and community support also ensure long-term maintainability.</p>

<h4>5.2 Google Gemini AI for Website Generation</h4>
<p>Google Gemini was selected over other LLMs (such as OpenAI GPT-4 or Anthropic Claude) because:</p>
<ul>
  <li>It offers a generous free tier suitable for a no-cost tool targeting small businesses.</li>
  <li>The Gemini API supports structured prompt engineering, enabling predictable HTML output.</li>
  <li>Multiple model variants (gemini-3-flash-preview, gemini-2.0-flash, etc.) allow a fallback mechanism, ensuring high availability.</li>
  <li>Gemini&rsquo;s multi-modal capabilities provide scope for future enhancements such as image-based product cataloguing.</li>
</ul>

<h4>5.3 Static HTML Output (Single-File Architecture)</h4>
<p>The decision to generate a single, self-contained HTML file (with embedded CSS and JavaScript) was driven by:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Zero Hosting Dependency:</b> The file can be hosted on free platforms (GitHub Pages, Netlify) or even shared via WhatsApp/email.</li>
  <li><b>Maximum Performance:</b> No server-side rendering, database queries, or API calls at runtime. The page loads instantly.</li>
  <li><b>Security:</b> Static pages have a minimal attack surface compared to dynamic websites with server-side processing.</li>
  <li><b>Simplicity:</b> Shopkeepers can understand the concept of &ldquo;one file = one website,&rdquo; lowering the barrier to adoption.</li>
</ul>

<h4>5.4 WhatsApp as the Ordering Channel</h4>
<p>WhatsApp was chosen as the ordering mechanism instead of traditional e-commerce checkout flows because:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Over 535 million Indians already use WhatsApp, making it the most familiar digital communication tool.</li>
  <li>No payment gateway integration needed&mdash;the shopkeeper and customer negotiate payment (cash on delivery, UPI, etc.) directly in the chat.</li>
  <li>The WhatsApp click-to-chat API (<code>wa.me</code> links) requires no business account setup or API keys.</li>
  <li>It provides a personal, trust-building interaction between the shopkeeper and customer.</li>
</ul>

<h4>5.5 Agile Development Methodology</h4>
<p>An Agile methodology with iterative development sprints was adopted to allow continuous feedback incorporation from the supervisor, frequent deliverables, and the flexibility to adjust features based on testing outcomes. The 16-week plan is structured into two-week sprints with defined deliverables at each stage.</p>

<!-- ================================================================== -->
<!--                  6. DISSERTATION METHODOLOGY                       -->
<!-- ================================================================== -->
<div class="page-break"></div>

<h3>6. Dissertation Methodology</h3>

<p>The dissertation follows a structured software development lifecycle (SDLC) approach, divided into the following phases:</p>

<h4>6.1 Requirement Gathering</h4>
<p>The initial phase involves identifying and documenting the requirements for the system. This includes:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Primary User Research:</b> Understanding the needs of small shopkeepers through informal surveys and conversations with local business owners to identify their pain points in establishing an online presence.</li>
  <li><b>Functional Requirements:</b>
    <ul>
      <li>Business information input form (name, type, description, contact details)</li>
      <li>Product listing input form (name, price, unit, image)</li>
      <li>AI-driven HTML page generation using Google Gemini</li>
      <li>WhatsApp &ldquo;Order Now&rdquo; integration per product</li>
      <li>Preview with desktop/mobile toggle</li>
      <li>Single-file HTML download</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><b>Non-Functional Requirements:</b>
    <ul>
      <li>Page generation within 30 seconds</li>
      <li>Mobile-responsive output</li>
      <li>Cross-browser compatibility</li>
      <li>Accessibility compliance (WCAG 2.1 Level A)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4>6.2 Use Case Design</h4>
<p>The system supports the following primary use cases:</p>

<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Use Case ID</th>
    <th>Use Case Name</th>
    <th>Actor</th>
    <th>Description</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-01</td>
    <td>Enter Business Details</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper fills in business name, type, description, and contact information through a guided form.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-02</td>
    <td>Add Products</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper adds one or more products with name, price, unit type, and image URL.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-03</td>
    <td>Generate Website</td>
    <td>System (AI)</td>
    <td>Gemini AI processes inputs and generates a complete HTML page with tailored design and WhatsApp links.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-04</td>
    <td>Preview Website</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper previews the generated website in both desktop and mobile views within the application.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-05</td>
    <td>Download Website</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper</td>
    <td>Shopkeeper downloads the generated HTML file to their device for deployment.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>UC-06</td>
    <td>Order via WhatsApp</td>
    <td>Customer</td>
    <td>Customer browses the static website and clicks &ldquo;Order on WhatsApp&rdquo; to initiate an order with pre-filled message.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h4>6.3 System Architecture</h4>
<p>The system follows a client-side-only architecture with the following components:</p>

<p><b>Architecture Overview:</b></p>
<pre>
+----------------------------------+
|        React Application         |
|      (Client-Side Browser)       |
+----------------------------------+
|                                  |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|  |     BusinessForm.js        |  |   Step 1: Collect business info
|  +----------------------------+  |
|              |                   |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|  |     ProductForm.js         |  |   Step 2: Collect product details
|  +----------------------------+  |
|              |                   |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|  |     gemini.js              |  |   AI Service: Prompt &rarr; Gemini API
|  |     (API Integration)      |  |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|              |                   |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|  |   WebsitePreview.js        |  |   Step 3: Preview &amp; Download
|  +----------------------------+  |
|                                  |
+----------------------------------+
              |
              | HTTPS API Call
              v
+----------------------------------+
|     Google Gemini AI API         |
|       (Cloud Service)            |
|  - gemini-3-flash-preview        |
|  - gemini-2.0-flash              |
|  - gemini-2.0-flash-lite         |
+----------------------------------+
              |
              | Returns generated HTML
              v
+----------------------------------+
|      Static HTML Output          |
|      (Single .html file)         |
|  - Embedded CSS &amp; JS             |
|  - WhatsApp order links          |
|  - Responsive design             |
|  - Product catalogue grid        |
+----------------------------------+
</pre>

<p><b>Data Flow:</b></p>
<ol>
  <li>Shopkeeper enters business details and product information through the React forms.</li>
  <li>The application constructs a detailed prompt incorporating all business data, product listings, and design preferences.</li>
  <li>The prompt is sent to the Google Gemini API with the instruction to generate a complete, single-file HTML page.</li>
  <li>A multi-model fallback mechanism attempts generation across multiple Gemini models with retry logic to ensure reliability.</li>
  <li>Gemini returns the generated HTML code, which is parsed and rendered in a sandboxed iframe for preview.</li>
  <li>The shopkeeper can toggle between desktop and mobile views, view fullscreen, and download the file.</li>
  <li>End customers visiting the generated page can browse products and initiate WhatsApp orders via pre-filled <code>wa.me</code> links.</li>
</ol>

<h4>6.4 UI/UX Prototyping</h4>
<p>The UI design follows a minimalist, mobile-first approach with the following principles:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Progressive Disclosure:</b> Information is collected across two sequential steps rather than a single overwhelming form.</li>
  <li><b>Visual Feedback:</b> Progress indicators, loading animations with real-time generation logs, and image previews for product URLs.</li>
  <li><b>Responsive Design:</b> Both the generator application and the output websites are fully responsive.</li>
  <li><b>Familiar Patterns:</b> Standard form elements, clear labels, and intuitive add/remove product controls.</li>
  <li><b>Accessibility:</b> Semantic HTML, proper contrast ratios, and keyboard-navigable forms.</li>
</ul>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h4>6.5 Development</h4>
<p>Development is carried out in iterative sprints:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Sprint 1&ndash;2:</b> Project setup, React application scaffolding, and business form component with validation.</li>
  <li><b>Sprint 3&ndash;4:</b> Product form component with dynamic add/remove, image preview, and unit type selection.</li>
  <li><b>Sprint 5&ndash;6:</b> Google Gemini API integration, prompt engineering, and multi-model fallback logic.</li>
  <li><b>Sprint 7&ndash;8:</b> Website preview component with iframe rendering, desktop/mobile toggle, and fullscreen view.</li>
  <li><b>Sprint 9&ndash;10:</b> WhatsApp ordering integration, download functionality, and output quality refinement.</li>
  <li><b>Sprint 11&ndash;12:</b> CSS animations, loading states, error handling, and UX polish.</li>
</ul>

<h4>6.6 Search Implementation</h4>
<p>The generated websites include a lightweight CSS-only product filtering mechanism and well-structured HTML sections with anchor-based navigation, enabling quick access to product categories within the static page. The product grid layout supports intuitive visual scanning, and the navigation bar provides smooth-scroll links to each section.</p>

<h4>6.7 Testing</h4>
<p>A comprehensive testing strategy is employed:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Unit Testing:</b> React component testing using Jest and React Testing Library for form validation, state management, and component rendering.</li>
  <li><b>Integration Testing:</b> End-to-end testing of the generation pipeline (form input &rarr; API call &rarr; HTML output).</li>
  <li><b>Output Validation:</b> Testing generated HTML for:
    <ul>
      <li>W3C HTML validity</li>
      <li>Responsive design across viewports (320px to 1920px)</li>
      <li>WhatsApp link functionality on Android, iOS, and desktop</li>
      <li>Cross-browser compatibility (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><b>Usability Testing:</b> Testing with 3&ndash;5 non-technical users (representing the target shopkeeper demographic) to validate ease of use.</li>
  <li><b>Performance Testing:</b> Measuring generation time, page load time of output, and Google Lighthouse scores.</li>
</ul>

<h4>6.8 Deployment</h4>
<ul>
  <li>The generator application is deployed on a free hosting platform (Netlify / Vercel) for public access.</li>
  <li>Generated static websites can be deployed by users on any static hosting service (GitHub Pages, Netlify, or served locally).</li>
  <li>CI/CD pipeline using GitHub Actions for automated build and deployment of the generator application.</li>
</ul>

<h4>6.9 Documentation</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Technical documentation covering system architecture, API integration, and code structure.</li>
  <li>User guide with step-by-step instructions for shopkeepers.</li>
  <li>Deployment guide for hosting the generated websites.</li>
  <li>Dissertation report with all findings, methodologies, and outcomes.</li>
</ul>

